Well-posedness of the linearized problem

For the case of variable coefficients the counterpart of the secondary symmetrization (79) for the linearized "vacuum" system reads B0 t V + B1 1 V + B2 2 V + B3 3 V = 0 where B1 = 1 1 - B1 - I t - - B2 2 - - B3 3 - . in T , (115)

We can prove the equivalence of systems (54) and (115). Lemma 6.1. Assume that the functions i (t, x) satisfy the hyperbolicity condition (78) and systems (54) and (115) have common initial data satisfying constraints (58) for t = 0. Assume also that the corresponding Cauchy problems for (54) and (115) have a unique classical solution on a time interval [0, T ]. Then these solutions coincide on [0, T ]. Lemma 6.1 can be proved with minor modifications of the proof of corresponding lemma from [14], where a hyperbolic -regularization was used for the elliptic system of pre-Maxwell dynamics. We just refer the reader to [14] in this connection. 32

For variable coefficients the counterpart of (85) reads t,x  = a ^1 HN |x1 =0 + a ^2 HN |x1 =0 + a ^3 vN |x1 =0 + a ^0 , (116)

